<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06066238 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06066238 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; BASKETBALL; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Minnesota beat the Los Angeles Lakers for the first time in franchise historyTuesday night as Tony Campbell scored 11 of his 25 points in the third quarterto help the Timberwolves to a 94-85 victory in Minneapolis.;    Los Angeles,which never led, shot 41 percent from the field.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  TIMBERWOLVES BEAT LAKERS FOR FIRST TIME  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  BasketballNBA Roundup  </MEMO><TEXT>     &quot;We're going to lose some games, and we know that,&quot; said Magic Johnson, wholed the Lakers with 32 points. &quot;But we're not supposed to lose this way. Wegot out-hustled, outrebounded and beat to loose balls.&quot;;    The Lakers scoredjust 37 points over the first two quarter, their lowest first-half total ofthe season.; SUNS 107, KNICKS 102: Tom Chambers scored 32 points and KevinJohnson 29 as streak-busting Phoenix won in New York.;    The Suns, whopreviously stopped winning streaks of 16 games by the Los Angeles Lakers, 11games by Detroit and Portland and seven by Boston, ended the Knicks' longestwinning streak of the season at five games.;    Patrick Ewing, who scored 36points, cut the Knicks' deficit to 101-100 on a turnaround jumper with 1minute, 9 seconds to play, but Johnson scored on a drive, Dan Majerleconnected on a jumper and Chambers made two free throws on the Suns' nextthree possessions to seal the victory.; SPURS 104, 76ERS 99: San Antonioerased a 17-point first-quarter deficit as David Robinson scored 33 points andgrabbed 16 rebounds to rally the Spurs past visiting Philadelphia.;    Thegame marked the return of San Antonio's David Wingate, who was signed to athree-year contract after being cleared of rape charges in San Antonio andMaryland last week. Wingate scored six points in 19 minutes.; CAVALIERS 113,SUPERSONICS 111: John Morton's off-balance 15-foot bank shot at the buzzergave visiting Cleveland an overtime victory over Seattle, snapping the Sonics'five-game winning streak.;    Morton, who scored a career-high 21 points, tiedthe game 101-101 with 0.8 seconds left in regulation with a driving layup.;   The Sonics appeared to have won the game on Ricky Pierce's 25-footer at theend of regulation, but the officials ruled that time had expired beforePierce's shot.;    Sonics guard Sedale Threatt left after the first half toreturn home to Louisiana for the funeral of his father, who died earlyTuesday.; HAWKS 139, NUGGETS 127: Spud Webb scored a career-high 32 points tolead Atlanta to its 22nd consecutive home victory, over Denver.; BULLS 104,BUCKS 86: Michael Jordan scored 30 points as Chicago won its 21st consecutivehome game, beating Milwaukee.; OTHER GAMES: In Indianapolis, Reggie Millerscored 22 points, grabbed 10 rebounds and handed out 10 assists to lead theIndiana Pacers over the Charlotte Hornets 112-101. Pacers forward Chuck Personwas sent to the hospital for X-rays with a possible concussion after collidingwith teammate Greg Dreiling in the opening minutes of the third period. . . .Eric &quot;Sleepy&quot; Floyd scored 27 points and Akeem Olajuwon came off the bench toadd 18 points and 12 rebounds as the Houston Rockets beat the visiting NewJersey Nets 112-100. Houston's Larry Smith sat out the game because of asprained left ankle. . . . Sherman Douglas scored 27 points, including thego-ahead basket with 11.9 seconds to play, as the Miami Heat beat the visitingLos Angeles Clippers 116-112 for a club-record 19th victory. Miami won 15games in its first season and 18 in its second. Assistant coach Dave Wohlfilled in for Heat Coach Ron Rothstein, who missed the game because of theflu. Los Angeles played without leading scorer Ken Norman, who was placed onthe injured list earlier in the day because of a sprained left ankle.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION